qas.question: What would be required for the human body to potentially have a chance to create a complete protein source?
Other than rice, what would be another example of an incomplete protein source?
What is taken from proteins and converted to glucose by the body?
What is the term for the conversion of amino acids into glucose?
What happens to amino acids that are left over after the body has converted what it can to glucose?

context: It is possible with protein combinations of <a0_0>two incomplete protein sources<a0_0/> (e.g., rice and <a1_0>beans<a1_0/>) to make a complete protein source, and characteristic combinations are the basis of distinct cultural cooking traditions. However, complementary sources of protein do not need to be eaten at the same meal to be used together by the body. <a2_0>Excess amino acids<a2_0/> from protein can be converted into glucose and used for fuel through a process called <a3_0>gluconeogenesis<a3_0/>. The amino acids remaining after such conversion are <a4_0>discarded<a4_0/>.
